e sure – we have to get out there and find out!<br>
<br>
I think intelligence is inevitable though. Life expands, it grows. Life on earth has reached every point it can. The only way life can continue to expand is to get off of the earth, and the only way to do that is to have an intelligence do it (that would be us).<br>
<br>
Now, life on other planets (should it exists, and I am fairly sure it must) will try and do the same thing. But if we are alone, if the universe is sterile save for us, it is incumbent upon us to expand - if we don’t we doom not only ourselves but our progeny and every other form of life both current and to come to extinction.<br>
<br>
Back to the Classics, anyone remember Azimov's “End of Eternity”? A great book in which a bloated buercracy that controls time travel (Eternity) uses its power to manipulate humanity to keep it safe. In the end humanity dies out because by keeping them safe they kept them from exploring and growing; even though humanity was one of the first intelligent species, by the time they finally begin to expand they find space filled with no place for them. The book concerns humans (well, a human) from the very end of time trying to destroy Eternity and give humanity a chance. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Dr. Carstairs</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 158<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/28/03 2:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Extraterrestial inteligence in the Galaxy</span><hr size=1> 1. The following facts apply:<br>
1. The Velocity of light is the absolute limit on all<br>
space travel, and communication in the universe.<br>
2. Slow nonrelavistic starflight at say 10% to 20%<br>
 of light velocity using fusion powered starships is<br>
 probably the norm for most star faring civilizations<br>
in the galaxy.<br>
3.The best practical, and economical  onboard power<br>
source, and propulsion system :that is both probably and <br>
actually available in practice to most advanced civilizations,<br>
 is either a thermonuclear direct thrust nuclear pulse  drive,  or a thermonuclear powered electric propulsion  drive.<br>
Both may be used  in either rocket or ramjet vessels.<br>
4. Protium fusion takes place to slowly to be used as a practical artificial energy source for starships.For this <br>
reason fusion powerd starships must be powered by either ,the D2 + D2 fusion reaction, or the D2 + T3 fusion reaction..<br>
5. This is because antimatter is a synthetic fuel that must literally be made 1 antiproton at a time in 1-2 Gev particle<br>
accelerators. This makes it probibitively expensive,and exceptionaly difficult to obtain in qauntity for use as starship fuel.* <br>
6. The galaxy is so large  because of being made of more<br>
 then 100,000,000,000 stars that technical civilizations <br>
advanced enough for interstellar  spaceflight are very far<br>
 from each other, such as a distance of  50 to 100 light years <br>
or more.If the average distance between star faring civilizations is about 50 to 100 light years it takes 500 to 1000 years of flight time at .10 C or so to get anywhere close to the nearest other advanced civilization.The circumferance of the galaxy is perhaps 160,000 light years, and the <br>
maximium  thickness of the galaxy is  perhaps 60,000 light years<br>
 <br>
7.In all regions of the galaxy except for the central hub,<br>
of the galaxy and the dense globular star clusters of the<br>
galaxy  such as the Pleides, the star systems are usaully<br>
at least 4-5 light years apart, and this requires at least a<br>
 40 to 50 year flight times at .10 C to travel between merely ajacent stars.<br>
8. All though some flt loopholes exist in theorectical physics<br>
these ftl solutions to the einstein eqautions are un-physical<br>
because they rely on unobtainable configurations of mass,<br>
and energy. This means there is no warp drive or hyperdrive<br>
that can be achieved in practice as hardware, not now :not ever. <br>
9. Only one type of ftl travel can ever be achieved in practice. This is the kind that results from relatavistic <br>
time dilation. For Example at .99 C (99% light speed)  there<br>
is a seven fold time dilation factor which provides a <br>
practical velocity of .99 * 7 C =  6.93 C <br>
(6.93 times the speed of light. At .99 C you can go to the star Aldeberan at 68 light years distance  in just about<br>
10 or so years in ship time if you can acclerate at 1 G, or you could go to the pleides star cluster at 400 light years from the solar system  in about 40-50 years of ship time at .99 C..<br>
10. There are only four practical methods of accelerating<br>
 close enough to light speed to achieve major time dilation factors., and thus attain relatavistic star travel .<br>
 11. These are:<br>
 1. MAtter-antimatter annhilation powered <br>
Pion rockets. <br>
2. laser/maser/solar light sails<br>
3. Laser/maser electric powered rockets, and ramjets<br>
4. Nuclear fission, or fusion powered electric ion or plasma drive ramjets , , or mama  powered interstellar,ion or <br>
plasma propulsion ramjets with all onboard power sources.<br>
11. Non-technological,low tech , or preindustrial  civilizations <br>
are probably common place in the galaxy, but technologicaly<br>
advanced civilizations that can achieve even non relatavistic<br>
 star fllight at about .10 C  are probably rare, exceptional, few in number, and very far from each other across the star lanes in the galaxy.<br>
12. Starfaring faring civilizations that can go much faster<br>
then about 10% to 20% of light speed , and can achieve relatavistic  star travel at nearly as fast as light velocities <br>
 are probably even more rare in the galaxy then those that can achieve .10 C star travel.<br>
13, Our civilization is capable of achieving manned non relavistic star travel at about .10 C in the foreseeable future later in this century by means of thermonuclear pulse rockets,, and we can achieve  unmanned star travel with robot probes at nearly as fast as light velocities by means of <br>
laser/maser/solar light sails later in this century as well .<br>
14. We know that we are probably  the most advanced civilization  within a radius of about 50 light years from our solar system  in our part of the galaxy<br>
15. We know this because we would have detected the radio, and television signals, The emp signals from nuclear weapon testing, or the Em emmissions from alien starships by now if there were any tecgnologicaly advanced ones within 50 light years of the solar system.<br>
16. There could however be technicaly  less advanced, low tech, or preindustrial alein civilizations within the 50 light year radius of the solar system however. <br>
17. These lower tech  or preindustrial alein civilizations  would not be technicaly advanced enough for us to detect them without our sending a star probe, or a starship to their star system first to look for them.They also would be too <br>
primative to be able to detect us in the Sol system<br>
